social inventions and developed social structures and social processes that have enabled it to overcome some of the major obstacles faced by other worker cooperatives in the past. William Foote Whyte and Kathleen King Whyte describe the creation and evolution of the Mondragón cooperatives, how they have changed through decades of experience, and how they have struggled to maintain a balance between their social commitments and economic realities. The lessons of Mondragón apply most clearly to worker cooperatives and other employee-owned firms, but also extend to regional development and stimulating and supporting entrepreneurship, whatever the form of ownership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aProducer cooperativeszSpainzMondragón. 4aEurope. 4aLabor History. 4aSociology & Social Science.  aAdministrative Science.  aAmerican social science.  aContemporary Sociology.  aMondragÃ³n Corporation.  aOrganization Studies.  aOrganizational Development european.  aSpanish cooperative.  acommunity economic development.  acooperative employee ownership.  acooperative enterprise.  aemployee-owned firms.  aeuropean politics.  aeuropean worker relations.  aevolution of the MondragÃ³n cooperatives.  ahow to create a worker cooperative.  ainterest in worker cooperatives.  ainternational cooperative movement.  alabor relations case studies.  alabor relations.  aorganizational Sociology.  aorganizational practice.  aorganizational sociologists.  aorganizational theorists.  aqualitative methodologists of American social science.  aqualitative methodologists.  asocial anthropology of advanced organizations.  asocial scientists of administration.  aspanish business practices.  aspanish worker relations.  awork redesign programs.  aworker cooperative .  aworker cooperati